  lectureDescription: '<h1>Lecture Summary: Player Types and LocalClientId</h1><p>In
    this lecture, we defined <strong>player types </strong>and used the <strong>LocalClientId
    </strong>to assign roles to players. The server is assigned as the "<i>Cross</i>"
    player, and the client becomes the "<i>Circle</i>" player. We achieved this by
    creating an <strong>enum </strong>called PlayerType with values None, Cross,
    and Circle, ensuring clean and robust type management.</p><p>Using the <strong>OnNetworkSpawn
    </strong>callback in a NetworkBehaviour, we determined whether the local client
    is the server (Id 0) or a client (Id 1) and assigned the appropriate player type.
    When objects are spawned, their type is now determined by the player''s role.</p><p>To
    enforce turn-based gameplay, we introduced a <strong>currentPlayablePlayerType
    </strong>field on the server. The game only allows actions from the player whose
    turn it is, updating the turn after each move. With these improvements, the game
    now enforces player roles and turn-taking properly.</p>

